snippet.textDisplay: "All my American subscribers are probably thinkin': What the heck is he talking about?"  I know I don't speak for all of your American subscribers, but yes, kind of.  We are aware that 'football' means 'soccer' everywhere else but here, but sometimes (most of the time) we're not thinking internationally.  As soon as I saw Jaffa Cakes though, I was like, "Oh...  right...  soccer..."  (I actually like soccer better than football, but don't really follow either.)  I was initially curious, because American football players are monsters.  Then, I was intrigued again because I never considered the diet of a soccer player, because they're not big guys.  I guess it was interesting in a philosophical way.  Small guys who eat a lot by necessity vs. what you do.  Adebayo isn't a 'small guy' though.  I had a thought though - what if we saw a female athlete's diet?  What do you think of Leah Shutkever btw?  She seems like she can really eat.

snippet.textDisplay:
Apparently, due to the apes and monkeys, the 'right' way to open up a banana is from the opposite end towards the stem - and the benefit of it is that all those filaments, that occasionally stick to the banana when you open it from the side of the stem, will get off with the peeling. I can confirm it works, significantly less filaments left on the banana if any. But on the flip side it's fricking hard to open it that way without a knife or an apes teeth... :-P

The orange fruits certainly weren't oranges, would agree with your tangerine theory there, though.

A very happy and healthy new year to you and Mrs. Beard.
